partner, that's actually

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:29.890
an opportunity for men to have
discussions about relationships

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:31.190
and so on.

00:31:31.190 --> 00:31:35.310
Now his hypothesis was that
it actually, in some cases,

00:31:35.310 --> 00:31:36.990
helped their relationship.

00:31:36.990 --> 00:31:38.870
We never got to test
that hypothesis.

00:31:38.870 --> 00:31:41.790
But it's an interesting
thing to think about.

00:31:41.790 --> 00:31:44.790
And of course, the solution
doesn't have to be affairs.

00:31:44.790 --> 00:31:47.880
The solution could be, how
do we create support networks

00:31:47.880 --> 00:31:48.710
for men?

00:31:48.710 --> 00:31:50.574
Given that relationships
are more complex,

00:31:50.574 --> 00:31:52.240
not just for women,
but for men as well,

00:31:52.240 --> 00:31:54.920
how do we create social
networks for men?

00:31:54.920 --> 00:31:59.720
That we can discuss those
things and have better aspect.

00:31:59.720 --> 00:32:03.270
The other thing we learned--
so Ashley Madison, men joined.

00:32:03.270 --> 00:32:05.640
You know the site, right?

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:08.230
The tagline used to be,
