00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:40.383
that is underappreciated
in relationships.

00:40:40.383 --> 00:40:41.150
DAN ARIELY: Yeah.

00:40:41.150 --> 00:40:44.520
And I think the research on
that has not been that great.

00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:50.860
But we know, for example, that
people fight a lot about money.

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:52.860
And fighting about
money is fighting

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:55.580
about priorities in life.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:41:01.135
And some of those fights,
people don't really

00:41:01.135 --> 00:41:02.760
understand what
they're fighting about.

00:41:02.760 --> 00:41:04.801
They're not understanding
that this pair of shoes

00:41:04.801 --> 00:41:07.400
is not really about the shoes,
or that this beer is not

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:09.190
about this beer.

00:41:09.190 --> 00:41:12.320
So how do you give
people some freedom,

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:15.706
and some control,
and some joint goals,

00:41:15.706 --> 00:41:16.830
is something we don't know.

00:41:16.830 --> 00:41:20.230
I'm actually very
hopeful that we

00:41:20.230 --> 00:41:22.470
need some technological
solutions for that.

00:41:22.470 --> 00:41:25.270
So people are going
to be different.

00:41:25.270 --> 00:41:28.740
And there's a question of, what
is the best way for couples

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:30.930
to manage their
money, for example,

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:32.930
in a way that gives them
some individual freedom

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:35.950
without getting upset with
the other person, but also

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:38.119
some commonality in
terms of their goals?

00:41:38.119 --> 00:41:40.160
And I think there's all
kinds of interesting ways

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:44.190
to think about, how would
we design joint checking

00:41:44.190 --> 00:41:46.670
accounts, and separate
accounts, and how much would we

00:41:46.670 --> 00:41:49.100
put in each of those
if we wanted people

00:41:49.100 --> 00:41:51.090
to at least not
fight about money?

00:41:51.090 --> 00:41:53.199
So I think we have to
recognize that there

00:41:53.199 --> 00:41:55.240
are going to be fights
about all kinds of things.

00:41:58.070 --> 00:42:01.950
And I'm not sure we
can always explain

00:42:01.950 --> 00:42:06.980
every fight, what it is about,
but how do we prevent those?

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:09.830
One of the nicest differences
that we know about

00:42:09.830 --> 00:42:11.400
between men and
women is actually

00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:14.050
in dating, not in
a relationship.

00:42:14.050 --> 00:42:16.710
So you all know what
speed dating is about?

00:42:16.710 --> 00:42:18.590
Let's say there are
10 men and 10 women.

00:42:18.590 --> 00:42:22.210
And they talk to one
person for five minutes.

00:42:22.210 --> 00:42:24.780
Then we ring a bell,
all the men switch.

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:28.110
They talk to another person,
another bell, they switch.

00:42:28.110 --> 00:42:30.150
And at the end, they
give you a list.

00:42:30.150 --> 00:42:32.340
And they say, from
the 10 people I met,

00:42:32.340 --> 00:42:38.210
these are the four or five I
want to meet for a second date.

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:40.300
So imagine two
speed dating events.

00:42:40.300 --> 00:42:42.990
One has 10 men and 10 women.

00:42:42.990 --> 00:42:46.640
And the other one has
20 men and 20 women.

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:51.014
Now what happens to the number
of people you say yes to?

00:42:51.014 --> 00:42:52.680
What happens to the
number of people you

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:54.980
say I want to meet them again?

00:42:54.980 --> 00:42:56.590
It could have two models.

00:42:56.590 --> 00:42:58.300
You can have a
model that says, I'm

00:42:58.300 --> 00:43:01.310
going to pick the top
three or the top x.

00:43:01.310 --> 00:43:03.440
And if you have that
model, it wouldn't

00:43:03.440 --> 00:43:05.490
change whether you meet
10 people or 20 people

00:43:05.490 --> 00:43:07.940
because you just pick the top x.

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:10.270
Or you could say,
I have a threshold.

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:14.010
I'm going to pick
everybody who's above 8.

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:16.255
And then, of course,
if you pick above 8,

00:43:16.255 --> 00:43:19.300
when you move from 10 to 20,
there'll be twice as many--

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:22.676
on expectation-- people
who pass the threshold.

00:43:22.676 --> 00:43:24.050
So what do you
think happens when

00:43:24.050 --> 00:43:29.980
people move from a small speed
dating event to a large one?

00:43:29.980 --> 00:43:33.190
Do they have, let's call
it the budget approach,

00:43:33.190 --> 00:43:34.780
where they have a top x?

00:43:34.780 --> 00:43:36.460
Or do they have the
threshold approach,

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:39.824
which says everybody above 8?

00:43:39.824 --> 00:43:41.240
AUDIENCE: Somewhere
in the middle.

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:42.740
DAN ARIELY: Somewhere
in the middle?

00:43:42.740 --> 00:43:44.930
AUDIENCE: They probably
say yes to more people,

00:43:44.930 --> 00:43:47.310
but not on a one-to-one ratio.

00:43:47.310 --> 00:43:48.830
DAN ARIELY: OK.

00:43:48.830 --> 00:43:52.011
So every time you listen to a
talk, think about the question

00:43:52.011 --> 00:43:52.510
before.

00:43:52.510 --> 00:43:54.690
You just asked me about
gender differences, right?

00:43:54.690 --> 00:43:57.140
So there's a gender
difference here as well.

00:43:57.140 --> 00:43:58.920
So men and women
are very different.

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:02.660
Women basically behave
as if they have a budget.

00:44:02.660 --> 00:44:04.850
So when the group
becomes larger,

00:44:04.850 --> 00:44:07.890
women just become more
critical or more restrictive.

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:11.330
They just say yes to--
their threshold goes up.

00:44:11.330 --> 00:44:14.010
And men say yes to the
same-- they have a threshold.

00:44:14.010 --> 00:44:14.890
Everybody over 8.

00:44:14.890 --> 00:44:17.080
So their number
basically doubles.

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:20.380
So this is actually one
of the biggest differences

00:44:20.380 --> 00:44:23.160
we've documented in dating.

