00:49:08.150 --> 00:49:10.140
would look at their
profile, what would it

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:12.015
be about them that you'd
say, oh my goodness,

00:49:12.015 --> 00:49:14.930
I want to be friends with
this person for 20 years.

00:49:14.930 --> 00:49:19.420
Is it their height,
eye color, BMI?

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:21.630
I mean, what?

00:49:21.630 --> 00:49:24.070
It's kind of crazy.

00:49:24.070 --> 00:49:26.630
And this is actually,
I think, a good point

00:49:26.630 --> 00:49:29.320
to think about at Google.

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:32.740
Why do we describe people
this way in online dating?

00:49:32.740 --> 00:49:34.760
Because it's easy.

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:37.220
It's meaningless
from the perspective

00:49:37.220 --> 00:49:40.150
of predicting who you would
actually like or don't like.

00:49:40.150 --> 00:49:43.311
But it's easy to do, and
it's easy to search on.

00:49:43.311 --> 00:49:45.560
But just because it's easy
to do and easy to search on

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:47.300
doesn't mean it's
the right mechanism.

00:49:51.350 --> 00:49:54.210
Look, I want people
to find love.

00:49:54.210 --> 00:49:55.290
It's a wonderful thing.

00:49:55.290 --> 00:49:57.030
We should promote that.

00:49:57.030 --> 00:49:59.420
But the companies who
are doing it, I think,

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:01.500
are taking tremendous shortcuts.

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:06.310
They're trying to do things that
are easy rather than effective.

00:50:06.310 --> 00:50:07.629
And it's a real shame.

00:50:07.629 --> 00:50:09.170
LOGAN URY: So what
question would you

00:50:09.170 --> 00:50:11.170
ask that you think would
actually be predictive?

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:21.740
DAN ARIELY: So I think I would
not ask questions, actually.

00:50:21.740 --> 00:50:23.230
So let's think
about online dating.

00:50:23.230 --> 00:50:26.820
What is the process of this?

00:50:26.820 --> 00:50:28.520
Is the process screening?

00:50:28.520 --> 00:50:30.670
Here are all the people
I don't look like.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:31.809
I think that's OK.

00:50:31.809 --> 00:50:33.350
I think you could
basically say, here

00:50:33.350 --> 00:50:35.650
are the people I
would never like.

00:50:35.650 --> 00:50:38.140
And I don't think we even need
to show them to you to know

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:39.308
that you don't like them.

00:50:42.300 --> 00:50:45.160
So we did a study in which
we said, look, dating

00:50:45.160 --> 00:50:47.120
is a very special thing.

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:51.042
Dating is actually going
through a shared experience.

00:50:51.042 --> 00:50:52.500
And through this
shared experience,

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:54.410
you get to do something.

00:50:54.410 --> 00:50:58.250
So we did a speed dating
event in an old people home.

00:50:58.250 --> 00:51:02.094
This was not for sexual
activity, necessarily,

00:51:02.094 --> 00:51:03.760
but we wanted people
to meet each other.

00:51:03.760 --> 00:51:05.470
They just moved to
an old people home.

00:51:05.470 --> 00:51:07.670
And the first time
we did it was a bust.

00:51:07.670 --> 00:51:11.540
They were just sitting there,
like, what do you talk about?

00:51:11.540 --> 00:51:15.210
And then we asked them to
bring a meaningful object

00:51:15.210 --> 00:51:17.040
from their life.

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:19.480
And the discussions
were amazing.

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:23.900
And people got engaged, and
shared experience, and so on.

00:51:23.900 --> 00:51:28.330
So if I was doing online
dating, I would say,

00:51:28.330 --> 00:51:31.682
I want to do something where
people will share an experience

00:51:31.682 --> 00:51:33.640
in a quick and efficient
way so they don't have

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:35.640
to travel a long
distance and so on,

00:51:35.640 --> 00:51:39.350
but it will give them a sense of
what the other person is like.

00:51:39.350 --> 00:51:42.470
So would it be solving
a puzzle together?

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:45.210
Or would it be listening
to music together?

00:51:45.210 --> 00:51:48.710
It could be all kinds of things.

00:51:48.710 --> 00:51:52.120
Facing moral dilemmas
of what do you do.

00:51:52.120 --> 00:51:54.620
I think all of
those things would

00:51:54.620 --> 00:51:58.200
be more effective than
something like this.

00:51:58.200 --> 00:52:00.270
So I think we're
confusing two things.

00:52:00.270 --> 00:52:02.480
There's the sorting
mechanism that

00:52:02.480 --> 00:52:04.520
says there's too many
people, let me just focus

00:52:04.520 --> 00:52:06.430
on the group I care about.

00:52:06.430 --> 00:52:08.180
But when you say the
group you care about,

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:10.330
it's probably a large group.

00:52:10.330 --> 00:52:12.840
You shouldn't sort it
too much because you miss

00:52:12.840 --> 00:52:15.390
some really wonderful people.

00:52:15.390 --> 00:52:19.060
And then we need a
different procedure.

00:52:19.060 --> 00:52:20.880
I had an idea once.

00:52:20.880 --> 00:52:23.880
How many people here
think that you're not

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:27.570
that good in making
first impressions?

00:52:27.570 --> 00:52:30.490
OK, quite a few of us.

00:52:30.490 --> 00:52:31.910
Online dating
right now is really

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:35.350
built for people who could go
to and pick up people in a bar.

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:37.060
It's not very different.

00:52:37.060 --> 00:52:39.820
Imagine if you had a dating
website only for people

00:52:39.820 --> 00:52:43.310
who don't do well in
first impressions,

00:52:43.310 --> 00:52:44.920
and you had a
different procedure.

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:46.220
And you say, you know what?

00:52:46.220 --> 00:52:48.340
Let's agree that
meeting somebody

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:51.210
for coffee for 15 minutes
is not really the solution.

00:52:51.210 --> 00:52:54.100
Let's agree that we'll meet for
three times over three weeks.

00:52:54.100 --> 00:52:56.070
We'll not come up to
judgments too early.

00:52:56.070 --> 00:52:57.460
And let's try to
create something

00:52:57.460 --> 00:53:00.770
where people actually--

00:53:00.770 --> 00:53:02.660
I'm not recommending
the dorm experience

00:53:02.660 --> 00:53:04.930
where you're locked with
somebody for a semester,

00:53:04.930 --> 00:53:07.290
but let's make something
where you actually

00:53:07.290 --> 00:53:11.700
are committed to finding
out something about somebody

00:53:11.700 --> 00:53:14.230
for a while rather than having
these quick judgments which

00:53:14.230 --> 00:53:15.880
I think are awful.

00:53:15.880 --> 00:53:17.080
Not so good.

00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:20.360
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
the Ashley Madison episode.

00:53:20.360 --> 00:53:22.680
And I read an article
after that came out

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:27.490
